Univariate plots¶

In [9]:
def univariate_plots(Source):
    a = pd.Series(Source.select_dtypes(include=['float64','int64']).columns)
    leng = len(a)
    for j in range(0,len(a)):
        f, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 10))
        sns.boxplot(Source[a[j]], ax = axes[0])
        sns.distplot(Source[a[j]], ax = axes[1])
        plt.subplots_adjust(top =  1.5, right = 10, left = 8, bottom = 1)

univariate_plots(dataset)

Observations from the univariate analysis

  1. cement - Mean is slightly more that the Median suggesting a slight positive skewness. No outliers.
  2. slag - Heavy positive skewness. Outliers present
  3. ash - Heavy positive skewness. No outliers present
  4. water - Mean is less than the Median, that means there is slight negative skewness. As seen from the boxplot, there are outliers present
  5. superplastic - There appears to be Gaussian mixtures (multiple modes). Outliers are present as seen in boxplot
  6. coarseagg - Mean is slightly greater than Median, suggesting slight positive skewness. No outliers present
  7. fineagg - There appears to be Gaussian mixtures. Also, there is a slight positive skewness. Outliers present.
  8. age - Multiple Gaussian mixtures. Mean is greater than Median suggesting postive skewness. Many outliers as seen from boxplot
  9. strength - Mean is very close to Median. Slight positive skewness. Boxplot suggests outliers.

def EDA_Corr(df):
        """This gives output as Covariance matrix and feature wise uniquess i.e how much its statistically
        independent. This is done with default range of corr between +0.5 to -0.6"""
        corr = df.corr()
        index = corr.columns
        Output = []
        for i in range(0,len(index)):
            i = index[i]
            Pos = corr.index[(corr[i] >= 0.5)].tolist()
            No = corr.index[(corr[i] < 0.5) & (corr[i] > -0.6)].tolist()
            Neg = corr.index[(corr[i] <= -0.5)].tolist()
            leng_u = len(No)
            leng_pos = len(Pos)
            leng_neg = len(Neg)
            Out = [i, leng_u, leng_pos, leng_neg, Pos, Neg, No]
            Output.append(Out)
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20,7)) 
        cmap = sns.diverging_palette(230, 20, as_cmap=True)
        sns.heatmap(corr,annot=True,vmin=-1,vmax=1,cmap=cmap, linewidths=0, ax = ax)
EDA_Corr(dataset)

From the pair plot and the Correlation matrix, it appears that there not a very significant correlation between various attributes. However,

  • There appear to correlation between Superplastic and water
  • There seem to be some correlation between water and fineagg
  • There seem to be some correlation between cement and strength
  • There seem to be some correlation between ash and superplastic

Treating ouliers¶

We will be opting for a strategy of replacing the outliers by NaN and then imputing NA values with medians

In [16]:
for col in cols:
    Q1=dataset[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3=dataset[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR=Q3-Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1-1.5*IQR
    Upper_Whisker = Q3+1.5*IQR
    dataset[col][dataset[col]> Upper_Whisker] = np.nan
    dataset[col][dataset[col]< Lower_Whisker] = np.nan

Explore for gaussians¶

If data is likely to be a mix of gaussians, explore individual clusters and present your findings in terms of the independent attributes and their suitability to predict strength

Pair plot suggest that there are Gaussian mixtures.

We will use clustering techniques to identify if there are possible clusters within the dataset

Techniques employed to squeeze that extra performance out of the model without making it overfit or underfit¶

We will the technique of grid search to get that extra performance from the model. Since the best performing model is Gradient Boost; hence the technique will be applied on it.

Model performance range at 95% confidence level¶

In [100]:
cvscores = cross_val_score(reg, X, y, cv = 10)
In [101]:
CV_score_mean = cvscores.mean()
CV_score_std = cvscores.std()

print("The mean score value is:", CV_score_mean, " and the std is:", CV_score_std)

The mean score value is: 0.9236294910303802  and the std is: 0.03050275844195084
In [102]:
sns.distplot(cvscores)
Out[102]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x22b5de6fb48>

For the scores in the range mean (+-) 2*std we can be certain of the scores with 95% confidence

In [103]:
print("Range of scores for 95% confidence is {} and {}".format((CV_score_mean-2*CV_score_std), 
                                                               (CV_score_mean+2*CV_score_std)))

Range of scores for 95% confidence is 0.8626239741464785 and 0.9846350079142818

We can assure with 95% confidence that the accuracy scores of gradient boost regressor with hyper parameters (learning_rate=0.1, max_depth=4, n_estimators=300, random_state=1, subsample=0.75) will have a accuracy of 86.2% and 98.4%
